Synset.Definition: that which is perceived or known or inferred to have its own distinct existence (living or nonliving)
an entity that has physical existence
a general concept formed by extracting common features from specific examples
a separate and self-contained entity
a tangible and visible entity; an entity that can cast a shadow
Synset.Example: it was full of rackets, balls and other objects

Synset.Definition: an assemblage of parts that is regarded as a single entity
Synset.Example: how big is that part compared to the whole?
the team is a unit

Synset.Definition: a whole (a thing or person) of the same kind or category as another
Synset.Example: lard was also used, though its congener, butter, was more frequently employed
the American shopkeeper differs from his European congener

Synset.Definition: a living (or once living) entity
a living thing that has (or can develop) the ability to act or function independently
organisms (plants and animals) that live at or near the bottom of a sea, lake, river or stream
a plant or animal that is atypically small
an organism that depends on complex organic substances for nutrition
an organism (plant or animal) from which younger ones are obtained
living things collectively
Synset.Example: the oceans are teeming with life

Synset.Definition: a discrete unit of living matter
(biology) the basic structural and functional unit of all organisms; they may exist as independent units of life (as in monads) or may form colonies or tissues as in higher plants and animals
any entity that produces an effect or is responsible for events or results
a human being; person, singular, assertive existential pronoun; pronoun, person, singular; quantifier: assertive existential
Synset.Example: there was too much for one person to do

Synset.Definition: a living organism characterized by voluntary movement
(botany) a living organism lacking the power of locomotion
indigenous plants and animals
an object occurring naturally; not made by man
the real physical matter of which a person or thing consists
Synset.Example: DNA is the substance of our genes

Synset.Definition: a particular kind or species of matter with uniform properties
Synset.Example: shigella is one of the most toxic substances known to man

Synset.Definition: that which has mass and occupies space
Synset.Example: physicists study both the nature of matter and the forces which govern it

Synset.Definition: any substance that can be metabolized by an animal to give energy and build tissue
any substance (such as a chemical element or inorganic compound) that can be taken in by a green plant and used in organic synthesis
a man-made object taken as a whole
one of a class of artifacts
Synset.Example: an article of clothing

Synset.Definition: a feature of the mental life of a living organism
the psychological result of perception and learning and reasoning
the psychological feature that arouses an organism to action toward a desired goal; the reason for the action; that which gives purpose and direction to behavior
Synset.Example: we did not understand his motivation
he acted with the best of motives

Synset.Definition: an abstraction belonging to or characteristic of an entity
the way something is with respect to its main attributes
Synset.Example: the current state of knowledge
his state of health
in a weak financial state

Synset.Definition: the experiencing of affective and emotional states
Synset.Example: she had a feeling of euphoria
he had terrible feelings of guilt
I disliked him and the feeling was mutual

Synset.Definition: a point or extent in space; a point or extent in space
the spatial arrangement of something as distinct from its substance
Synset.Example: geometry is the mathematical science of shape

Synset.Definition: the continuum of experience in which events pass from the future through the present to the past
Synset.Example: he waited for along time
it took some time before he got an answer
time flies like an arrow

Synset.Definition: the unlimited expanse in which everything is located
Synset.Example: they tested his ability to locate objects in space
the boundless regions of the infinite

Synset.Definition: physical space independent of what occupies it
(physics) an ideal space in which the coordinate dimensions represent the variables that are required to describe a system or substance
Synset.Example: a multidimensional phase space

Synset.Definition: something that happens at a given place and time
a sustained phenomenon or one marked by gradual changes through a series of states
Synset.Example: events now in process
the process of calcification begins later for boys than for girls

Synset.Definition: something that people do or cause to happen
any number of entities (members) considered as a unit
an abstraction belonging to or characteristic of two entities or parts together
anything owned or possessed
a relation between living organisms (especially between people)
something that is communicated by or to or between people or groups
how much there is or how many there are of something that you can quantify
any state or process known through the senses rather than by intuition or reasoning
